    "creation_date" : 1277881543,
    "answer_id" : 3147081,
    "question_id" : 3144610,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<blockquote>\n  <p>I don't like casting primitives, who knows what may happen.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Why do you have an irrational fear of casting primitives? Nothing bad will happen when you cast an <code>int</code> to a <code>double</code>. If you're just not sure of how it works, look it up in the <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se7/html/index.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Java Language Specification</a>. Casting an <code>int</code> to <code>double</code> is a <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se7/html/jls-5.html#jls-5.1.2\" rel=\"noreferrer\">widening primitive conversion</a>.</p>\n\n<p>You can get rid of the extra pair of parentheses by casting the denominator instead of the numerator:</p>\n\n<pre><code>double d = num / (double) denom;\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 333393,
      "reputation" : 936,
      "user_id" : 659238,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 50,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/nHGnF.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "alianos-",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/659238/alianos"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 35,
    "last_activity_date" : 1428072174,
    "last_edit_date" : 1428072174,
    "creation_date" : 1369301749,
    "answer_id" : 16710392,
    "question_id" : 3144610,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>If you change the type of one the variables you have to remember to sneak in a double again if your formula changes, because if this variable stops being part of the calculation the result is messed up. I make a habit of casting within the calculation, and add a comment next to it.</p>\n\n<pre><code>double d = 5 / (double) 20; //cast to double, to do floating point calculations\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Note that casting the result won't do it</p>\n\n<pre><code>double d = (double)(5 / 20); //produces 0.0\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
