    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 5958144,
      "reputation" : 22558,
      "user_id" : 4684058,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 100,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/vhz3N.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Minhas Kamal",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4684058/minhas-kamal"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 26,
    "last_activity_date" : 1596693059,
    "last_edit_date" : 1596693059,
    "creation_date" : 1460020390,
    "answer_id" : 36471636,
    "question_id" : 3144610,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<h1><a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se7/html/jls-5.html#jls-5.5\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Type Casting</a> Is The Only Way</h1>\n<p>May be you will not do it explicitly but it will happen.</p>\n<p>Now, there are several ways we can try to get precise <code>double</code> value (where <code>num</code> and <code>denom</code> are <code>int</code> type, and of-course <em>with casting</em>)-</p>\n<ol>\n<li>with explicit casting:</li>\n</ol>\n<ul>\n<li><code>double d = (double) num / denom;</code></li>\n<li><code>double d = ((double) num) / denom;</code></li>\n<li><code>double d = num / (double) denom;</code></li>\n<li><code>double d = (double) num / (double) denom;</code></li>\n</ul>\n<p>but not <code>double d = (double) (num / denom);</code></p>\n<ol start=\"2\">\n<li>with implicit casting:</li>\n</ol>\n<ul>\n<li><code>double d = num * 1.0 / denom;</code></li>\n<li><code>double d = num / 1d / denom;</code></li>\n<li><code>double d = ( num + 0.0 ) / denom;</code></li>\n<li><code>double d = num;    d /= denom;</code></li>\n</ul>\n<p>but not <code>double d = num / denom * 1.0;</code><br />\nand not <code>double d = 0.0 + ( num / denom );</code></p>\n<hr />\n<p>Now if you are asking- Which one is <strong>better</strong>? explicit? or implicit?</p>\n<p>Well, lets not follow a straight answer here. Simply remember- We programmers don't like surprises or magics in a source. And we really hate Easter Eggs.</p>\n<p>Also, an extra operation will definitely not make your code more efficient. Right?</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 306208,
      "reputation" : 19436,
      "user_id" : 616815,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 100,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/22815981387e5a9b49b737c0a317ade1?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Ken Wayne VanderLinde",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/616815/ken-wayne-vanderlinde"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1472832402,
    "creation_date" : 1472832402,
    "answer_id" : 39296670,
    "question_id" : 3144610,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>You might consider wrapping the operations. For example:</p>\n\n<pre><code>class Utils\n{\n    public static double divide(int num, int denom) {\n        return ((double) num) / denom;\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>This allows you to look up (just once) whether the cast does exactly what you want. This method could also be subject to tests, to ensure that it continues to do what you want. It also doesn't matter what trick you use to cause the division (you could use any of the answers here), as long as it results in the correct result. Anywhere you need to divide two integers, you can now just call <code>Utils::divide</code> and trust that it does the right thing.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 10697174,
      "reputation" : 31,
      "user_id" : 7873838,
      "user_type" : "registered",
